CAPE TOWN - Two suspects have been detained for questioning in connection with a robbery at the Brackenfell Post Office on Tuesday. According to reports, four armed men entered the premises in Paradys Street, threatening the staff demanding cash at around 1pm. No shots were fired and no one sustained any injuries. That night, Metro police officers who were busy with crime prevention patrol received information about a suspicious vehicle in the area. The suspects aged 27 and 36 were allegedly found with a large sum of money and were arrested. Metro Police spokesperson, Ruth Solomons said the suspects could not give a proper explanation of where the money came from. “The vehicle was spotted on CCTV cameras driving away from an armed robbery earlier at the post office and CCTV operators noted the same vehicle exploring the Brackenfell area around 10pm. “The officers stopped and searched the vehicle on the R300 close to the Van Riebeeck off-ramp in the direction of the N2. Officers found a large amount of money under the driver's seat covered with a cloth and around R15 000 in the passengers’ possession. The total amounted to R32 279,” said Solomons. Police spokesperson Joseph Swartbooi said two males aged 27 and 36 are being detained for questioning at Brackenfell SAPS. “The circumstances surrounding a business robbery that occurred in Brackenfell, on Tuesday, at around 12:50pm, are under investigation. The investigation continues,” said Swartbooi. Anyone with information can anonymously contact Crime Stop at 086 0010 111 or SMS Crime Line at 32211. Cape Times